08735nam a22010335i 9780812296754DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122967547 a10.9783/97808122967542doi  a(DE-B1597)563419  a(OCoLC)1156230582  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a248.4/466223  aBD 1400qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/9835:00aBastards and Believers :bJewish Converts and Conversion from the Bible to the Present /ced. by Paweł Maciejko, Theodor Dunkelgrün. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b1 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Term Ger and the Concept of Conversion in the Hebrew Bible -- tChapter 2. Ex- Jews and Early Christians: Conversion and the Allure of the Other -- tChapter 3. Conversion to Judaism as Reflected in the Rabbinic Writings and Culture of Medieval Ashkenaz: Between Germany and Northern France -- tChapter 4. Of Purity, Piety, and Plunder: Jewish Apostates and Poverty in Medieval Eu rope -- tChapter 5. “Cleanse Me from My Sin”: The Social and Cultural Vicissitudes of a Converso Family in Fifteenth- Century Castile -- tChapter 6. Converso Paulinism and Residual Jewishness: Conversion from Judaism to Chris tianity as a Theologico- political Problem -- tChapter 7. Return by Any Other Name: Religious Change Among Amsterdam’s New Jews -- tChapter 8. The Persuasive Path: Giulio Morosini’s Derekh Emunah as a Conversion Narrative -- tChapter 9. “Precious Books”: Conversion, Nationality, and the Novel, 1810–2010 -- tChapter 10. Between European Judaism and British Protestantism in the Early Nineteenth Century -- tChapter 11. When Life Imitates Art: Shtetl Sociability and Conversion in Imperial Russia -- tChapter 12. Opposition, Integration, and Ambiguity: Toward a History of the Israeli Chief Rabbinate’s Policies on Conversion to Judaism -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA formidable collection of studies on religious conversion and converts in Jewish historyTheodor Dunkelgrün and Pawel Maciejko observe that the term "conversion" is profoundly polysemous. It can refer to Jews who turn to religions other than Judaism and non-Jews who tie their fates to that of Jewish people. It can be used to talk about Christians becoming Muslim (or vice versa), Christians "born again," or premodern efforts to Christianize (or Islamize) indigenous populations of Asia, Africa, and the Americas. It can even describe how modern, secular people discover spiritual creeds and join religious communities.Viewing Jewish history from the perspective of conversion across a broad chronological and conceptual frame, Bastards and Believers highlights how the concepts of the convert and of conversion have histories of their own. The volume begins with Sara Japhet's study of conversion in the Hebrew Bible and ends with Netanel Fisher's essay on conversion to Judaism in contemporary Israel. In between, Andrew S. Jacobs writes about the allure of becoming an "other" in late Antiquity; Ephraim Kanarfogel considers Rabbinic attitudes and approaches toward conversion to Judaism in the Middles Ages; and Paola Tartakoff ponders the relationship between conversion and poverty in medieval Iberia. Three case studies, by Javier Castaño, Claude Stuczynski, and Anne Oravetz Albert, focus on different aspects of the experience of Spanish-Portuguese conversos. Michela Andreatta and Sarah Gracombe discuss conversion narratives; and Elliott Horowitz and Ellie Shainker analyze Eastern European converts' encounters with missionaries of different persuasions.Despite the differences between periods, contexts, and sources, two fundamental and mutually exclusive notions of human life thread the essays together: the conviction that one can choose one's destiny and the conviction that one cannot escapes one's past. The history of converts presented by Bastards and Believers speaks to the possibility, or impossibility, of changing one's life.Contributors: Michela Andreatta, Javier Castaño, Theodor Dunkelgrün, Netanel Fisher, Sarah Gracombe, Elliott Horowitz, Andrew S. Jacobs, Sara Japhet, Ephraim Kanarfogel, Pawel Maciejko, Anne Oravetz Albert, Ellie Shainker, Claude Stuczynski, Paola Tartakoff.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aChristian converts from Judaism. 0aConversionxChristianityxHistory. 0aConversionxJudaismxHistory. 0aJewish Christians. 0aJewish converts from Christianity. 0aJewsxConversion to Christianity. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aJewish history.  areligious conversion.1 aAlbert, Anne Oravetz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndreatta, Michela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastaño, Javier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunkelgrün, Theodor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunkelgrün, Theodor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFisher, Netanel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGracombe, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorowitz, Elliott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Andrew S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaphet, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanarfogel, Ephraim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaciejko, Paweł, econtr